      <bioghist>
         <head>Biographical/Historical Information</head>
         <p>Marvin Leonard Colker was born on March 19, 1927 in
         Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania and married Hazel Robinson (a
         graduate of Trinity College, Dublin and the Royal Irish
         Academy of Music) on November 28, 1959. After earning a B.A.
         in classics summa cum laude from the University of Pittsburgh
         (1948), Colker went on to Harvard University for his doctorate
         (1951). His dissertation was a critical edition of a 12th
         century Latin epic, the 
         <title render="italic">Alexandreis</title>of Gautier de
         Chatillon. The poem, celebrating the deeds of Alexander the
         Great, was available to scholars only in inauthentic form
         based on poor manuscripts; Colker's dissertation redressed
         these problems and was revised and published in 1978. After
         two postgraduate fellowships (including a Fulbright fellowship
         at the University of Paris), Colker joined the faculty of the
         University of Virginia as instructor of classics (1953). He
         has taught at Virginia ever since, serving as the chairman of
         the Department of Classics (1963-1968) and becoming a full
         professor (1967- ). He has also served the University of
         Dublin in several capacities, including cataloguer of medieval
         manuscripts (1958-) and lecturer in patristics (1962-1963).
         Trinity College at the University of Dublin awarded Colker an
         honorary Doctor of Letters degree in 1987. In addition to his
         edition of Gautier's poem, Colker's publications include 
         <title render="italic">Fulcoii Belvacensis
         Epistolae</title>(1954), 
         <title render="italic">Analecta Dublinensia: Three Medieval
         Latin Texts in the Library of Trinity College,
         Dublin</title>(1975), and 
         <title render="italic">America Rediscovered in the Thirteenth
         Century</title>(1979). A member of scholarly associations
         including Phi Beta Kappa and the Medieval Academy of America,
         he has been a Guggenheim fellow (1973-1974) and currently
         holds a second Fulbright fellowship (1987- ), which has taken
         Colker to England and Ireland for research.</p>
         <p>For a more complete chronology of Colker's career, see the 
         <title render="italic">Dictionary of American
         Scholars</title>and 
         <title render="italic">Who's Who in America</title>.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent>
         <head>Scope and Content Information</head>
         <p>The collection consists of two archival accessions
         interfiled together with ca. 2500 items (1.7 shelf feet) and
         dates from 1943 to 1989. It is comprised mainly of
         correspondence with American and European scholars concerned
         with classical studies and Latin paleography. There are also
         various newsclippings detailing the professional advancement
         of Colker and various colleagues; catalogs of manuscript
         collections; and scholarly and general interest articles
         Colker wrote.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      <arrangement>
         <head>Organization</head>
         <p>The first three boxes contain incoming correspondence; Box
         3 also contains Colker's outgoing correspondence. Box 4
         contains research on various topics, including work with
         manuscripts in the Alderman Library of the University of
         Virginia; catalogs of manuscripts; financial papers;
         curriculum vitae and an autobiographical sketch; newspaper
         clippings; information concerning fellowships and membership
         in professional organizations; and teaching material.</p>
      </arrangement>
